Create a new Spring Boot module called `frontend-service` that serves as a server-rendered
web UI for an Online Food Delivery System. This service has NO REST API of its own — it is
a pure MVC frontend that calls the backend microservices exclusively through the API Gateway
(api-gateway) using RestTemplate or WebClient (blocking mode).

STRICT CONSTRAINTS:
- Thymeleaf + HTML + CSS only. NO JavaScript, NO JS frameworks, NO fetch/AJAX, NO <script> tags.
- All interactivity (forms, navigation, filters, pagination) must work via standard HTML forms
  (GET/POST) and full page reloads — no client-side scripting of any kind.
- Authentication: user logs in via a login form; frontend-service calls auth-service (through
  the gateway) to get a JWT, then stores the JWT server-side in the HttpSession (never in a
  cookie or localStorage, never exposed to the browser). Every backend call attaches this JWT
  as a Bearer token via an Authorization header, added server-side.
- Use Spring Security only for session management / access control on frontend-service routes
  (not for issuing tokens — that's auth-service's job). Protect routes by role using role stored
  in the session.

TECH STACK:
- Java 21, Spring Boot 3, Maven
- Spring Web (MVC), Thymeleaf, Spring Security (session-based, form login flow)
- RestTemplate (or WebClient in blocking .block() mode) for calling the gateway
- Lombok, SLF4J for logging
- No database — this service is stateless except for the HTTP session

ROLES & PAGES (build one controller + templates per role):
1. GUEST (unauthenticated): landing page, browse restaurants/menus (read-only), login, register
2. CUSTOMER: browse restaurants, view menu, add to cart (via POST forms, cart held in session),
   checkout/place order, view order history, view order status, leave review
3. RESTAURANT OWNER: manage own restaurant profile, manage menu items (CRUD via forms), view
   incoming orders, update order status
4. DELIVERY PERSON: view assigned deliveries, update delivery status
5. ADMIN: list/manage customers, restaurants, orders; basic dashboard with summary stats

PROJECT STRUCTURE:
- src/main/java/.../frontend/config       -> SecurityConfig, RestTemplateConfig, WebClient/Gateway base URL config
- src/main/java/.../frontend/controller    -> one controller per role/domain (AuthController,
  CustomerController, RestaurantOwnerController, DeliveryController, AdminController)
- src/main/java/.../frontend/dto           -> plain DTOs mirroring backend API request/response shapes
- src/main/java/.../frontend/client        -> thin client classes per backend service
  (AuthServiceClient, RestaurantServiceClient, OrderServiceClient, etc.), each wrapping
  RestTemplate calls to the gateway with the JWT header attached
- src/main/java/.../frontend/session       -> helper for storing/retrieving JWT + user role/id
  from HttpSession
- src/main/resources/templates             -> Thymeleaf templates, organized in subfolders per
  role (templates/customer/, templates/restaurant/, templates/delivery/, templates/admin/,
  templates/auth/), plus a shared templates/layout/ with a Thymeleaf fragment for header/nav/footer
- src/main/resources/static/css            -> hand-written CSS (no CSS framework unless I ask
  for Bootstrap explicitly), organized as base.css + one file per section if needed

DESIGN / VISUAL REQUIREMENTS:
- Clean, professional, modern look — NOT a default-Bootstrap or toy/childish appearance.
- Consistent design system: define CSS custom properties (variables) for a small color palette
  (e.g. one primary brand color, a neutral gray scale, one accent/success/danger color), spacing
  scale, and a clean sans-serif font stack.
- Use a shared layout fragment (header with logo/nav based on role, footer) included via
  Thymeleaf th:replace/th:insert across all pages so styling stays consistent.
- Card-based layouts for restaurant/menu listings, clean tables for order/admin lists, clear
  visual hierarchy (headings, whitespace, subtle borders/shadows rather than heavy colors).
- Responsive basics (flexbox/grid, no fixed pixel-locked layouts) but desktop-first is fine.
- Every form should have proper labels, validation error display (from Spring's BindingResult),
  and clear primary/secondary button styling — all still purely HTML/CSS, no JS validation.

INTEGRATION DETAILS:
- API Gateway base URL should be externalized via application.yml (e.g. gateway.base-url).
- Each *ServiceClient class should have clear methods per endpoint (e.g.
  RestaurantServiceClient.getAllRestaurants(), .getMenuByRestaurantId(id)), returning DTOs,
  and should throw/handle errors so controllers can show a friendly error page/flash message
  on failure (e.g. backend down, 401/403, validation errors from backend).
- Use Spring's flash attributes (RedirectAttributes) for post-redirect-get success/error
  messages, since there's no JS for toasts/alerts.

